			<title>Homework</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76835-Homework&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sat, 24 May 2014 11:09:12 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I remember when I was younger. You couldn't get me to do homework if you baited me with a trip to Disneyland laced with a can of Coca Cola, and a bowl of Top Ramen (these were delicate days in the Gill Household, I might have only had two twinkies in my life at the time).  
 
I had dreams of dirt...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I remember when I was younger. You couldn't get me to do homework if you baited me with a trip to Disneyland laced with a can of Coca Cola, and a bowl of Top Ramen (these were delicate days in the Gill Household, I might have only had two twinkies in my life at the time). <br />
<br />
I had dreams of dirt bikes, and surf boards, and climbing Mount Everest. I still dream of Mount Everest. Some part of me still wants to sit my old man on the peak and break the world record for the oldest man to summit the highest geological point on this floating rock of space (and he'd do it, too, telling stories about Jerry Connors all the way to the top, and everyone else he used to go on his crazy backpacking trips with). <br />
<br />
Seeing better in hindsight, as I always do, it was that active need to be a part of something creative that was always keeping me from doing my homework.<br />
<br />
It wasn't until I was involved in the High School marching band that I started to give a darn about anything academic (besides chasing girls I had absolutely no chance with). <br />
<br />
If I didn't hold a C average (which might sound simple for the majority of my friends) I couldn't play in the pep band, the jazz band or the marching band. It gave me new focus. It set a bar. If I could manage to get the classes I was good at (band, spanish) to outweigh the classes I couldn't keep my brain straight on (math, english, science), I could maybe harness that 2.0 GPA to keep me in those extra curricular activities that got me in and out of day and night and kept me going on from point A to point B with a smile on my face, and not a hunch in my shoulders. <br />
<br />
It wasn't until I got the freedom of a Driver's License, a stunning set of wheels (subtitled 1986 Toyota Corolla that belonged to my golf pro grandfather before he suffered from his life and freedom debilitating stroke), and a desire to explore the roads of my very own city that I'd never driven down before, that I finally had a creative interest to make school projects into something that were just a little bit bigger than the minimum requirements to *pass.* <br />
<br />
I set myself a goal a little time before receiving my Driver's License. I wanted to be king of the band nerds. That title has its very own, in “Drum Major” for those in the know., and for the moment it was all I needed to succeed in getting that Driver's License, too. <br />
<br />
If I kept my grades good, and did extremely well in the classes that kept my GPA up, I would gear myself better to not only be Drum Major, but also have the 3.0 GPA my parents required of me to get Driver’s Ed classes. <br />
<br />
I hadn't quite learned the concept of end-game objective, maybe just skirmish survival and success. It was enough to get me to latch onto some small idea of first-world hope. <br />
<br />
As time went on, and I succeeded in these projects that I'd set in front of me, I never bothered to set additional goals (well, maybe have a girlfriend, but that was either hit-or-miss along the way). Without having learned the concept of a long-term goal setting, my short-term objectives became end-game procedures, and I never prepared for the steps after. Waving a baton seemed good enough for survival.<br />
<br />
After I graduated high school, I really had no idea what I was supposed to do next. I followed the tides of chaos that everyone else in my predicament seemed to do. I attended the local community college and enrolled in classes that sounded interesting. I was even marked by the music program as a desirable, and asked to join a couple of the performance ensembles. I couldn’t see an end-game, or a goal in any of them, so i continued to list. I continued to enroll in classes and drop out of them. I couldn’t find anything creative to hold onto. <br />
<br />
Those years while I tried to find whatever pathway that I was destined to follow; that I was so forcefully molded through in the duress of my formulative years was no longer a cast constraining my path, but the freedom itself became a crutch. Without the guidance of force, I listed; floated through those ethereal planes of reason that lack motivation.<br />
<br />
Sometimes, I succeeded. Sometimes, I failed, and hit rock bottom. Sometimes, time, and time again. <br />
<br />
Somehow, I survived.<br />
<br />
Somehow, I joined a band that spoke spanish (ZING!).<br />
<br />
Somehow, I met the woman that I married (DOUBLE ZING!)<br />
<br />
Somehow, we were blessed by not only two beautiful boys, but also their creative stories that make us smile every day, and their cunning ploys that make us laugh harder than even the wittiest of our jokes on one another.<br />
<br />
On days like today,I find myself at work, where I hustle. I churn brain butter. I burn that midnight oil, and I work harder than I ever have in my entire life up until this moment, and I not only work hard, I work *smart.* <br />
<br />
In the company of others around me, I teach them how to do what I do, and how to learn how to do it without the need of asking for assistance, but to break things down methodically, and learn how it all works. <br />
<br />
In the back of my mind, I look at my title. I look at my function. I look at the beauty the job that puts food on my table provides my family, and I smile. <br />
<br />
Here I sit, making my own homework. Creating a reflection on my day. Making sure I learn important things from it. <br />
<br />
I didn't learn this in school. <br />
<br />
I learned it in my heart. And I will continue to look into my heart to know what things I need to learn, to do better at, and succeed. <br />
<br />
As Robert Frost was once quoted as saying, &quot;Love is an irresistible desire to be irresistibly desired.&quot;</div>

]]></content:encoded>
