			<description><![CDATA[In a vehicle, when you adjust the air to be hot or cold, this is done by what is called a Blend Door. The blend door motor on my truck appears to have died with the door stuck on heat. It was ok through the winter but now that we are hitting mid 80's at times... holy shit it gets hot. Time to...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>In a vehicle, when you adjust the air to be hot or cold, this is done by what is called a Blend Door. The blend door motor on my truck appears to have died with the door stuck on heat. It was ok through the winter but now that we are hitting mid 80's at times... holy shit it gets hot. Time to replace it, the dealer wanted over $300 so I figure I'll do it myself as the motor only cost $50 w/ shipping.<br />
<br />
My GoogleFu showed me its a common problem and the motor is a simple 2 screws to R&amp;R, easy! <br />
<br />
Armed with my tools I dive in... apparently there is a bezel that covers the motor, that has 3 screws. No biggie... oh wait, the 3rd one is in accessible due to center console covering it. Damnit!  :wtf:<br />
<br />
Google console removal instructions, its 2 nuts, 2 screws and unhooking a couple wiring harnesses. Ok whatever, I start removing it... it's bracket runs under the front seat brackets. WTF... ! So, I now end up tearing out both front seats, unhook all the airbag crap and wiring harnesses to those, yank'em out. Next I am able to manhandle the center console out and toss it next to the seats. Now I get the final screw out of the bezel and remove it: Wala, the blend door motor is sitting there easily accessable.<br />
<br />
Two screws it falls right out.<br />
<br />
/sigh :rlymad:<br />
<br />
<img src="http://www.huntingnut.com/images/temp/cab2.jpg" border="0" alt="" /><br />
<br />
I stuck only the front seat back in to make it drivable and left the rest out until the replacement motor arrives. I want to make sure the replacement works fine before I stick all the other crap back in. This motor appears to go bad frequently so it must be a cash cow for dealers because it requires so many shop hours to tear all the other shit out before you even get to the motor. <br />
<br />
Damn all you engineers that made it this way! :ohreally:</div>

]]></content:encoded>
