			<title>Not a complaint, but a rant none the less.</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76767-Not-a-complaint-but-a-rant-none-the-less&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 05 May 2014 07:00:18 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>MAN. My wife and I went swimming today with the kids, today.  
 
I spent yesterday putting some drywall up in a mold abatement project with a very old friend. He is the father of an ex-girlfriend, but I knew him for 10, maybe 15 years before his daughter and I ever dated, and he was always really...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>MAN. My wife and I went swimming today with the kids, today. <br />
<br />
I spent yesterday putting some drywall up in a mold abatement project with a very old friend. He is the father of an ex-girlfriend, but I knew him for 10, maybe 15 years before his daughter and I ever dated, and he was always really cool. Never thought I would be one who would work with his hands, but working with him a couple times the last 2 months, its a wonderful feeling working for a guy with just a real confident go-easy attitude verse the &quot;DO MORE DAMNIT&quot; attitude of my father in law.<br />
<br />
My father-in-law has his reasons (mostly because he is not his own boss, he has even bigger &quot;DO MORE DAMNIT&quot; attitude above him, so it has to be dealt with a trickle-down sort of discipline). I respect them. <br />
<br />
The difference between the two is great. I get paid less with the old friend, but I enjoy the work because it involves much more control and learning than what I've already built up with my Father-in-law boss. <br />
<br />
Yesterday, I came home to my very upset wife, because I was supposed to be home an hour earlier so I could get the dog to the vet and have him vaccinated, and even though I was still able to meet the necessary time frame to do so, and did, it stressed her out. The boys, who are learning potty training, literally soiled every bit of carpet that has been off limits to them before. They &quot;shit the bed&quot; so to speak. <br />
<br />
She is totally understanding of it all. Even though she knows he is my ex-girlfriend's father, she is very accepting of it. SHe knows I have always seen him as both a father figure and a friend, and that their family is close to me, but she knows that my relationship with him gets me closer and closer to my General Contractor's license. She understands my therapeutic need to build things, make things, use my tools, and be a true craftsman, and call shots. That is an amazing feeling. And at the end of the day when all promises are fulfilled she is okay with it. Hell, I'll even go uncensored on y'all and say that Saturday Night is definitely seated very well in the top 10, possibly top 5 most memorable evenings together as man and wife (and beyond). <br />
<br />
So today we went swimming. My brother in-law-in-law was there with his wife (my sister-in-law), my little sister, and all of our kids, and we had a ball. The pool was all to ourselves, and we just had a great time. The boys got closer to learning how to swim (I think my younger boy has no idea that he can drown, because he just kept jumping straight into the water when no one was even near him. Very crazy, and he huffed down water like it was crack on several occasions, followed by laughing and gurgling and coughing, not too distant from our adrenaline like screams. <br />
<br />
In all this, my wife took in a whole lot of sun. She has a beautiful, natural olive complexion in her skin-tone, and when she gets sunlight, she becomes <i>radiant</i>. <br />
<br />
Plus, she also has decided to start working out to almost Insanity proportions. She spent half an hour on a yoga mat doing all sorts of crazy things I'd never imagine her capable of. <br />
<br />
It reminded me of the first day I started my current job. Hard concrete demo work with jackhammer and all. After 2 hours of lugging 50 pounds of concrete at a time, I puked all over myself and the job site. THe guys I was working with thought I was suffering a heart attack. Maybe I was, but I managed to live through it, and still have my current job. Those guys aren't even with the company anymore - I guess the boss, the work, the compensation maybe? - it got to them and they're not longer here.<br />
<br />
Needless to say, after all the hard work, my wife was in inexorable pain, exhausted, and after getting the strength to get into the shower, she threw up in it. I knew it would happen. It happens to the best of us. Like me, she worried she was suffering a heart attack - maybe she was, maybe she wasn't. I doubt it though, I think she just taxed herself that much, and when you do, your body realizes it has toxins in there it needs to quickly get rid of, and it did. <br />
<br />
After all that vomit in the tub was washed down. Her trek down stairs almost left her incapable of getting back up (but she did), she still looked radiant. That sunlight drawing out more melatonin from her skin, her pores probably cleaned from both our years of sedentary lifestyle being flushed so quickly. She looked beautiful. <br />
<br />
In this big huge world filled with murder. People stabbing eachother. People killing eachother with baits and traps. <br />
<br />
For God's sake. I am not afraid to say I truly believe there is something bigger than just the human species for it to be so beautiful. I am truly happy to be where I am right now, and feel as though the future is wide open. I have to put my head down, and stare at the ground, because I have an intrinsic desire to never let pride consume me, but I am so thankful for these days my wife and I have together, where we get to sit down on the couch, in the quiet, with everyone in the house asleep, and just talk about these crazy things we go through, and we still manage to love eachother as much as we do. <br />
<br />
I hope that everyone has something as great as we have. Maybe just for a few minutes a day if that is all they can spare. When it happens, it is so glorious.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
